<HL>
   Hong Kong Bourse
   Studies Possibility
   Of Options Market
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5C
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
COMMODITY NEWS, FARM PRODUCTS (CMD)
</IN>
<LP>
   HONG KONG -- Options trading could start in Hong Kong
sometime next year if a preliminary study being carried out
by the stock exchange finds sufficient market interest.
   Brisk interest in stock and index options has been
expressed so far by most of the brokerage houses, investors
and regulators surveyed so far, according to John Parry, a
consultant with Trimedia Communications Ltd., a Swiss firm
that is making a two-month study of the issue.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The study is seeking to establish whether options would be
used by investors, how they would affect the colony's
financial market and what kind of training and promotional
programs they would require.
   "The reaction we've had so far has been very promising,"
Mr. Parry said. "It does suggest at this stage there is
certainly considerable interest."
   If the exchange decides to go through with the project,
the colony would become the fourth financial center in the
Asia-Pacific region to offer options trading, joining Sydney,
Tokyo and Singapore. The move is widely seen as part of the
exchange's effort to expand its products, which have grown
over the past year and a half with the addition of listed
debt instruments and unit trusts.
   But the expansion has come amid generally shallow turnover
on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange, and the failure of the
colony's futures exchange to regain much life after its near
failure following the October 1987 market crash.
   Robert Gilmore, an executive director at the Securities
and Futures Commission who has worked in options markets in
Chicago and Philadelphia, said stock options could give the
underlying market a boost, judged on patterns elsewhere.
   "History has proven to us that options aid in cash-market
liquidity," he claimed, adding that the U.S. options market
is responsible for a substantial amount of trading in the
underlying stocks listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
   He also argued that Hong Kong must come up with new
instruments to serve increasingly sophisticated investors or
risk losing its attractiveness as a major financial center.
   It would probably take the colony 12 to 15 months to come
up with the regulations and operating framework for options
to be traded if the preliminary study were accepted,
according to Mr. Parry. Among the changes is the alteration
of a law that currently prohibits options trading; that would
require approval by the colony's legislative council.
   One issue centers on how many local stocks have adequate
liquidity and capitalization, as well as sufficiently
widespread shareholding, to be suitable for options. Many
local concerns are controlled by single owners who often run
their day-to-day operations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0175
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0175.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Merry-Go-Round Enterprises Is Rolling
   Ahead, Aided by Woes of Big Retailers
   ----
   By Vindu P. Goel
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5F
</SO>
<CO>
   MGR
</CO>
<IN>
DOW JONES INTERVIEW (CEO)
</IN>
<LP>
   Aided by the troubles of bigger retailers, Merry-Go-Round
Enterprises Inc. expects to report first-quarter earnings of
$5.8 million to $6.2 million, or 26 cents to 28 cents a
share, substantially exceeding analysts' estimates, said
Michael D. Sullivan, president and chief executive officer.
   Analysts' estimates for fiscal first-quarter earnings
ranged from 10 cents a share to 17 cents a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Sales for the first quarter of fiscal 1991, which ended
May 5, were about $120.5 million. In the year-ago quarter,
the Joppa, Md., retailing chain posted earnings of $1.7
million, or eight cents a share, on sales of $73.9 million,
after restating for three stock dividends. In the current
year, Merry-Go-Round has about 6% more post-split shares
outstanding.
   A key factor in Merry-Go-Round's present financial
performance, Mr. Sullivan said, is the boom environment for
mall-based specialty apparel stores -- a consequence of the
financial difficulties of large retailers like Campeau Corp.
and Ames Department Stores Inc.
   With tightened credit from vendors, the large chains can't
stock new merchandise, Mr. Sullivan said. "If you can't get
fresh goods, you're like a person in quicksand. You're going
to go down. It's just a matter of when."
   Merry-Go-Round, on the other hand, has been turning
inventory at a rapid rate, about six times a year. "You have
to turn the goods to be in the fashion business," Mr.
Sullivan said. "You can't sit on dead stock," particularly
with the 15-to-25-year-olds who are the company's target
customers.
   To help avoid missing changes in consumer tastes,
merchandise staffers sit down every Monday morning and
examine what sold -- and what didn't -- in the previous week.
"It's not totally risk-free, but it's also not the total
crapshoot everyone thinks it is."
   Mr. Sullivan attributed some of Merry-Go-Round's
first-quarter earnings gain to a weak year-ago quarter, when
the company was saddled with start-up costs for a new
360,000-square-foot distribution center. In addition, the
company's April 1989 acquisition of 120 Silverman's stores
from Retail Ventures Inc. and Natco Industries Inc. increased
costs and diverted inventory from other stores.
   Although the remaining quarters won't show such a dramatic
improvement, Mr. Sullivan said he also sees strong earnings
growth for the rest of the year. He called analysts' 1991
earnings estimates of $1.35 to $1.40 a share "very attainable
and probably on the conservative side." Indeed, Mr. Sullivan
said he expects earnings for the fiscal year to be more like
$1.50 a share, or about $33.5 million, on sales of $600
million. In fiscal 1990, Merry-Go-Round earned a restated
$22.2 million, or $1.04 a share, on sales of $478.9 million.
   Merry-Go-Round's growth has left the company with $40
million in cash and a desire to expand further. This fiscal
year, the company plans to open 50 to 55 new stores and
expand others.
   And with the Silverman's acquisition well digested --
April same-store sales more than doubled at the chain -- Mr.
Sullivan is fishing for even more real estate. "It puts us in
an excellent position to look for opportunities," he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0174
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0174.
</DOCID>
