<HL>
   Economy:
   Fed Credit Policy Is Left Unchanged
   At Latest Meeting, Official Indicates
   ----
   By Alan Murray and Beatrice E. Garcia
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<IN>
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
</IN>
<GV>
FEDERAL RESERVE BOARD (FED)
</GV>
<LP>
   Faced with conflicting economic signals, the Federal
Reserve apparently decided to leave credit policy unchanged
at its meeting on Tuesday.
   Edward G. Boehne, president of the Philadelphia Federal
Reserve Bank, said yesterday that the Fed hasn't changed
monetary policy since right before Christmas. Other Fed
officials wouldn't comment directly, but didn't challenge Mr.
Boehne's comments.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   A few weeks ago, signs of rapid inflation were leading
some Fed officials to talk as if they might be ready to
tighten policy, and nudge up interest rates. But government
statistics released over the past week suggested the economy
was weaker and inflation less threatening than previously
thought.
   As a result, Fed officials now seem to think their best
policy may be to stay put. "The risk to the economy is fairly
even between a further slowdown and inflation," Mr. Boehne
told the Philadelphia Association of Retired Bankers.
   Mr. Boehne is currently a voting member of the Fed's key
policy committee, which is made up of five district reserve
bank presidents plus the members of the Fed's board of
governors.
   Some market analysts have in recent days begun to
speculate that the Fed may soon ease credit to help boost the
economy. But for his part, Mr. Boehne seems pleased with
current slow-growth rates. He said the economy has achieved
the hoped-for soft landing, and is now growing "at a moderate
pace that is sustainable."
   "I am reasonably optimistic about the whole economy as we
go forward," he said.
   The Fed eased monetary policy several times late last
year, with the most recent move occurring shortly before
Christmas. At the time, Mr. Boehne said, there was
considerable concern about recession. But despite the recent
weak economic numbers, he said, fears of recession have
receded.
   Earlier this year, the Fed was under heavy pressure from
the Treasury to bring down interest rates. Treasury officials
thought high U.S. rates were partly responsible for
attracting foreign investors and thus driving up the value of
the dollar relative to the Japanese yen. In the last few
weeks, however, the dollar's value has fallen significantly
against the yen, easing the Treasury's concerns.
   Mr. Boehne said that when the Fed does decide to move
again, it will continue to be in the small steps that have
characterized the central bank's action under the
chairmanship of Alan Greenspan. "Federal Reserve policy is
one of prudence," he said, "steady as she goes."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0169
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0169.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Canadian Panel
   Offers Solution
   In Quebec Dispute
   ----
   By John Urquhart
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   CANDA
</CO>
<LP>
   OTTAWA -- A Canadian parliamentary committee unanimously
recommended a plan to overcome a Canadian constitutional
impasse that has revived independence demands in Quebec.
   The impasse arose over proposed constitutional amendments
that would recognize Quebec, a largely French-speaking
province, as a "distinct society" within Canada and grant new
powers to provinces in areas such as immigration.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Much of the public's opposition to the changes has focused
on the proposed distinct society designation for Quebec, even
though constitutional lawyers have questioned whether the
clause would have much legal meaning.
   Prime Minister Brian Mulroney said designating Quebec a
distinct society doesn't mean the province "is privileged or
gains any special powers. It simply confirms the obvious:
that Quebec is different and that that difference is very
much worth conserving."
   The parliamentary committee, which held public hearings
across the country, said the constitutional proposals, known
as the Meech Lake Accord, should be left intact and ratified
by June 23, a legal deadline. But the panel also recommended
that the federal Parliament and the 10 provincial
legislatures also adopt a companion resolution addressing
concerns about the proposed distinct society designation for
Quebec and other constitutional issues.
   The parliamentary committee said that although the
distinct society clause won't give Quebec any additional
powers, the companion resolution, to allay public concern,
should declare that the province's special designation "in no
way" infringes the constitution's charter of rights.
   Mr. Mulroney said that "what is in dispute over the Meech
Lake Accord is very modest." But he said sentiment is so
strong that "the stakes involved in our constitutional
deadlock are enormous." The Meech Lake Accord, which was
negotiated in 1987 at Meech Lake, Quebec, was designed to
meet Quebec's "minimum" constitutional demands.
   A public opinion poll published earlier this week said 60%
of Quebecers now favor Quebec's becoming politically
independent while maintaining "an economic association with
the rest of Canada."
   The parliamentary committee's proposals provide a basis
for a resolution of the constitutional dispute by the federal
and provincial governments, said the committee's chairman,
Jean Charest. Three provinces, Manitoba, Newfoundland and New
Brunswick, oppose the Meech Lake Accord.
   Newfoundland Premier Clyde Wells said the committee has
made some recommendations that "point in a helpful
direction." New Brunswick Premier Frank McKenna also welcomed
the committee's report, saying it addressed New Brunswick's
concerns.
   Mr. Mulroney said he will "spare no effort to develop a
consensus and break the deadlock, if at all possible." But he
said he would call the provincial leaders to a constitutional
conference only if "there are reasonable prospects of
success."
   The parliamentary committee's recommendations included a
new, more flexible constitutional process for revising the
federal Senate, the appointed chamber of Parliament. Senate
overhaul is a major goal of several provinces.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0168
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
