   Group's Tender Offer
   For Debt of Allegheny
   International Expires
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   AG
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
BANKRUPTCIES (BCY)
</IN>
<LP>
   PROVIDENCE, R.I. -- Japonica Partners, a New York investor
group trying to take over Allegheny International Inc., said
it's cash tender offer for debentures of the troubled
consumer products concern expired yesterday.
   Japonica said it accepted for payment all of Allegheny's
9% subordinated sinking-fund debentures due 1989 at a price
of 39.8% of their principal amount; the 10 3/4% subordinated
sinking-fund debentures due 1999 at 41% of their principal
amount; the 10.4% subordinated sinking-fund debentures due
2002 at 27.7% of their principal amount, and the 9%
sinking-fund debentures due 1994 of Allegheny's Chemetron
unit at 83.8% of their principal amount that were tendered.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Based on a preliminary count, Japonica said the following
were tendered; $6.7 million principal amount of the 9%
subordinated sinking-fund debentures due 1989, representing
56% of such debentures outstanding; $47.7 million principal
amount of the 10 3/4% subordinated sinking-fund debentures
due 1999, representing 72% of such debentures outstanding;
$15.1 million principal amount of the 10.4% subordinated
sinking-fund debentures due 2002, representing 39% of such
debentures outstanding; and $6 million principal amount of
Chemetron's 9% sinking fund debentures due 1994, representing
36% of such debentures outstanding.
   Allegheny and several subsidiaries, including Chemetron,
have been operating under Chapter 11 of the federal
Bankruptcy Code.
