<HL>
   Interco Threatens a Chapter 11 Filing
   To Pressure Bondholders On Debt Plan
   ----
   By Francine Schwadel and George Anders
   Staff Reporters of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   ISS
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
</IN>
<LP>
   Interco Inc. threatened a bankruptcy-law filing in an
attempt to pressure bondholders into accepting its plan to
restructure almost $900 million in debt.
   The troubled St. Louis furniture and shoe company, which
borrowed heavily to recapitalize in late 1988, said it
doesn't intend to seek court protection from creditors under
Chapter 11 of the federal Bankruptcy Code "unless the
restructuring cannot otherwise be accomplished."
</LP>
<TEXT>
   But in a Securities and Exchange Commission filing, the
company said publicly for the first time that it viewed a
"prepackaged" Chapter 11 reorganization plan as an
"alternative method for accomplishing the restructuring."
   Bondholders have been grumbling about the plan, announced
last week. It offers little in the way of new interest-paying
bonds and, instead, relies heavily on issuing more Interco
common stock. As a result, some bondholders have suggested
they might fare better if they could push Interco into
Chapter 11.
   A company spokesman said, however, that Interco's Chapter
11 proposal involves "exactly the same offer with respect to
the terms we're offering to debenture holders and
shareholders." The only difference, he said, is that Chapter
11 requires approval by holders of two-thirds of each class
of bonds -- far fewer than the 90% needed for the debt-swap
offer.
   Moreover, he said the company's bank lenders wouldn't be
affected by the prepackaged bankruptcy filing. The banks, as
reported, are negotiating terms of an agreement that would
stretch out payments on $500 million in loans into 1992. The
banks already have extended until Oct. 1 the due date on
certain loan payments while they are in talks about amending
Interco's existing credit agreements.
   But disgruntled bondholders still could scuttle the plan.
If they fail to approve it in sufficient numbers, Interco
could still face a standard Chapter 11 filing that would
involve lengthy negotiations with all parties.
   Yesterday, in composite trading on the New York Stock
Exchange, Interco shares closed unchanged at 46.9 cents each.
   Interco and its advisers, J.P. Morgan &amp; Co. and Smith
Barney, Harris Upham &amp; Co., are believed to hope that a
prepackaged Chapter 11 filing could bring the company out of
bankruptcy-law proceedings within four months. In contrast, a
standard Chapter 11 petition could mean two years in
bankruptcy court.
   "The value of the business would almost certainly
depreciate substantially," if the company spent two years in
Chapter 11, according to one person familiar with the
restructuring. Interco makes Lane and Broyhill furniture and
Converse and Florsheim shoes.
   Interco sketched an optimistic financial picture if its
restructuring is accepted and its debt burden lightened. The
company said it could show net income of $55 million for the
year ending Feb. 29, 1992, and rising profits thereafter.
Operating cash flow -- net income plus taxes, interest and
depreciation, minus capital spending -- would cover its
interest bill by 1.67 times or better. Currently, Interco is
running losses and lacks the cash flow to service its debt.
   But Interco's projections require a lot of favorable
breaks, including steady annual sales growth of about 6%,
cost cuts of $75 million a year, and no big new
capital-spending projects. Bondholders with doubts about
Interco's prospects may decide that the restructuring plan
"isn't attractive," said Jerry Hirschberg, an analyst at
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp.
   Rather than swap bonds for equity in the
post-restructuring company, bondholders may press for more
cash from Interco. Otherwise bondholders may just "strap on
the hand grenades," reject the restructuring plan and see how
they fare in a full Chapter 11 filing, said Craig Davis, an
analyst at R.D. Smith &amp; Co.
   Interco's troubles date from its 1988 recapitalization,
when it borrowed almost $2 billion to pay shareholders
special dividends in cash and securities to fend off a
takeover threat from the Rales brothers of Washington D.C.
But asset sales have taken longer and generated less cash
than the company had expected. And its operations have fallen
short of expectations.
   Interco's bonds have sunk to such low levels that the
filing threat had little impact on bond prices. Interco's 13
3/4% debentures were quoted at about 26 cents on the dollar;
its two subordinated issues were quoted at about five cents
on the dollar.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0133
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0133.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   First Fidelity to Set Aside $300 Million
   For Bad Loans and Cut Dividend 40%
   ----
   By Robert Guenther
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   FFB
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
</IN>
<LP>
   LAWRENCEVILLE, N.J. -- Seeking to get to the bottom of its
barrel of loan problems, First Fidelity Bancorp. said it
expects to set aside as much as $300 million for past-due
loans in the second quarter and slash its dividend 40%.
   As a result, analysts said that they expect the parent of
New Jersey's largest bank to post a loss of about $130
million, or $2.25 a share, for the quarter. The bank didn't
forecast results. First Fidelity earned $63.3 million, or
$1.03 a share, a year earlier. For 1989, profit was $159.5
million, or $2.51 a share.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The bad news, the result of a stem-to-stern review of the
$20 billion loan portfolio ordered by the new chairman,
Anthony P. Terracciano, wasn't as dire as some had feared.
Some analysts had expected the bank to eliminate its dividend
-- not just cut it to 30 cents a share from 50 cents a share.
In response, First Fidelity shares staged their best showing
in recent months, climbing $1.875 to close at $19.50 a share
in New York Stock Exchange composite trading.
   In essence, the second quarter gives Mr. Terracciano, who
previously helped resurrect Pittsburgh-based Mellon Bank
Corp., a free shot at any loan made by the previous
management under former Chairman Robert R. Ferguson Jr. With
those loans behind him, he now must demonstrate that a
turnaround is under way and show some gains in the company's
listless core earnings and high overhead costs.
   Michael Plodwick, an analyst with C.J. Lawrence, Morgan
Grenfell, said: "This is where the honeymoon ends. Now
whatever happens is his."
   Once a hot "superregional" bank that was a darling of
investors, First Fidelity had been rudderless since late 1988
when problem loans were uncovered in Philadelphia and London
and the company posted a $176 million loss in that year's
fourth quarter. Mr. Ferguson's heir apparent, Harold Pote,
then president and chief executive officer, was forced to
resign as a result.
   Since taking the reins in January, Mr. Terracciano has
brought in fresh talent to newly created top positions, fired
about 10% of the work force, or 1,400 employees, and begun
consolidating back offices and more than 550 branches.
   Nevertheless, analysts remain worried about the direction
of the New Jersey-Pennsylvania economy and are holding off
recommending First Fidelity until the earnings outlook
becomes clearer.
   "Tony can do a lot, but he can't change the local
economy," said Felice Gelman, an analyst for Dillon, Read &amp;
Co.
   Mr. Terracciano said the increase in problem loans
reflects a weakening real estate market, a slowing economy,
and tougher examination standards being imposed by
regulators. He added that a significant portion of the $240
million or so increase in problem loans are ones on which
interest and principal payments are current. Normally banks
classify loans as nonperforming only when they are 90 days or
more past due; however, that practice has changed as
regulators have interpreted the term more conservatively.
   Even so, Mr. Terracciano said: "We presently anticipate
that the loan loss provision will return to a more normal
level in the third and fourth quarters. Thus, we expect First
Fidelity's performance in the second half of the year to more
clearly reflect its core earnings capacity."
   First Fidelity's capital and reserve levels aren't a cause
for concern. With nonperforming loans expected to rise to as
much as $850 million from $604 million as of March 31, First
Fidelity's reserves will stand at 75% of that amount even if
charge-offs double. The company's ratio of equity to assets
will drop to 4.2% from 4.7% but will remain above the 4%
level required by regulators.
   In a related move, Standard &amp; Poor's Corp. placed First
Fidelity's long-term and short-term debt issues under review
for possible downgrades. About $750 million of debt is
affected.
   Separately, First Fidelity said that it is seeking buyers
for its Fidelcor Business Credit Corp., an asset-based lender
in New York City, and Latimer &amp; Buck, a commercial mortgage
firm in Philadelphia. Mr. Terracciano said the units are
profitable but don't fit the company's long-term plans. The
sales are expected to be completed this summer.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0132
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0132.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Darker Forces Behind Romania's `Front'
   ----
   By Peter Keresztes
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A10
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP
</CO>
<LP>
   BUCHAREST -- The spectacular December upheaval blasted
away the top of the pyramid of Romania's Communist
dictatorship, but most of that massive structure stands
intact. Five months later, Ion Iliescu's National Salvation
Front, the engineer of the alteration, wants popular
endorsement for the project. Even the Front's foes think it
will get it.
   The students who have been holding rallies on University
Square demand the acceptance of Article 8 of the Timisoara
declaration -- which would bar most of the Front, as former
Communists, from politics for six years. But the students
seem to be playing into Mr. Iliescu's hands. He has called
them "hooligans" and has not yielded in any way to their
demands to postpone Sunday's national elections.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Front spokesman, Adrian Nastase, claims protesters are
trying to "invalidate" the election results before the
election. Thus, he insists, they are violating the Universal
Declaration of Human Rights. He also casts a few warning
words at Romanian television, controlled by the state, for
allowing itself to be "manipulated" by the students. He
regards the Front's willingness to give the students a
"speakers' corner" as a generous gesture.
   Generosity has its limits, particularly in the provinces,
out of range of most of the world press. Ion Ratiu, the
septuagenarian presidential candidate of the "rejuvenated"
Peasants Party, and Radu Campeanu, the somewhat younger
prospect of the Liberal Party, repeatedly ran for their lives
when Frontists in Tirgu Mures, Ordea and Braila physically
dispersed their audiences. The two have returned from many
years of self-exile in the West to lead the two parties that
are the main -- though apparently distant -- challengers
among the more than 80 groups taking on the Front.
   Mr. Nastase frowns on such incidents but asserts that the
culprits "act in their own capacity as private citizens" and
that the Front also has been hassled. Washing its hands of
such "police problems," it blames the murdered dictator
Nicolae Ceausescu and his predecessors back to 1938 for
having suppressed self-expression for too long.
   The Peasant and Liberal parties believe that the
international team of observers is too small to prevent
manipulation of the election results. That is plausible. But
risk of manipulation could be academic if the Front is as far
ahead as everyone seems to think. It has successfully
portrayed itself as Romania's savior.
   A less lofty purpose is beginning to emerge, however.
Romania Libera, an independent Bucharest daily, claims that a
transcript of a Front meeting shows the Front had been
preparing a takeover for at least six months before the
December explosion. Minutes after the Ceausescus fled, Petre
Roman, the current prime minister, was at party headquarters
-- to be joined shortly by Mr. Iliescu, Nicolae Miliearu, the
Front's first defense minister, Victor Stanculescu, the
current defense minister, and at least five others who were
to play a role in the Front. Diplomats say the Front's
18-point proclamation was too sophisticated to have been
produced on the spur of the moment. The Front was in touch
with the Soviet Embassy during the crisis, Romania Libera
claims.
   The Front's sincerity is also called into question by its
initial declaration that it would set up only a transitional
government and would not transform itself into a political
party. When it did, some supporters quit and nonstop protests
and hunger strikes began. In the wake of the Tirgu Mures
clashes between Transylvanian Hungarians and Romanians, the
Front ordered up a fact-finding committee. But it lost no
time in accusing the Hungarian government and travelers from
Hungary of having provoked the incidents.
   The most telling indictment of the regime, however, is the
fact that refugees are once again pouring out of Romania. The
flow had practically stopped in the first two months
following the fall of the Ceausescus. The average daily
number of arrivals in Hungary since mid-March has been 400 to
500. Austrian camps are jammed, so Austria has closed its
borders to Romanian refugees. The reasons for the flood
include the feeling in Romania that political intolerance
will intensify, exploitation of tensions among nationalities
will increase and the economy will weaken.
   Telephone taps have resumed, diplomats and politicians
swear. Literature once again is confiscated at the borders. A
guard who takes some of my historical reference books into
custody states that while it isn't illegal to bring them to
Romania, "it is inadvisable to do so now. In better times
this will not be necessary." So much for Prime Minister
Roman's ceremonious endorsement of the Helsinki document that
refers to the "free flow of ideas."
   The apparatus of repression is still intact. The
Securitate operates within the military under a new name,
Siguranta. The political police and the armed forces became
part of the Front's government as early as December,
according to a diplomatic veteran in Bucharest. The students'
suspicions about Front claims that "communism in Romania died
forever" seem well placed.
   Front nationalities policies fall short of the hopes its
rhetoric raised in December. Romania's rulers, like all
beleaguered regimes, continue to need what the Bucharest
diplomat calls an "enemy element" to serve as a distraction
from political and economic ills. In Romania, the more than
two million Transylvanian Hungarians fill most of this role.
In the wake of what they thought was their revolution too,
they proposed the restoration of their historic university in
Cluj along with the resumption of teaching in their mother
tongue in public schools. The response to such requests
included the formation of Vatra Romanesca, an
ultra-nationalist Romanian movement.
   Vasile Aileni, a vice president and council director of
the Front, says Vatra reflects Romanians' sensitivity over
Transylvania, which has been part of Romania since the end of
the first World War (except between 1940 and 1945 -- when
much of the province was annexed to Hungary). Hungary had
ruled the region for about a millennium. "Every country needs
a common language," he says. "And in Romania, the common
language is Romanian. If a Hungarian wants to study in his
language, he can go to Budapest, since everyone now has a
passport."
   To be sure, some things have improved. Since December the
cities are not as dark at night. People can and do criticize
politicians at the tops of their lungs. Food lines are fewer.
People can start small service businesses; they can own a
little land. Everyone has a passport (although no access to
hard currency for travel). And they now can vote.
   But the uncertainty is over what those votes are worth. As
Sunday's elections approach, a lot of Romanians think not
very much.
   ---
   Mr. Keresztes is deputy editorial-page editor of The Wall
Street Journal Europe. A related editorial appears today.
{See: "Review &amp; Outlook (Editorial): Reading Romania's
Future" -- WSJ May 18, 1990}
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
