<HL>
   Brazil Pressures
   Auto Industry
   With New Plan
   ----
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM F GM G.VOW FIA TOYOY
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
</IN>
<LP>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil -- Foreign-owned automobile plants,
leading players in Brazil's industrial development, are under
fire from a government that wants to open up the market.
   Brazil recently announced plans to allow the installation
of new automobile plants. The country's big four --
Volkswagen AG, Ford Motor Co., General Motors Corp. and Fiat
S.p.A. -- suddenly have found themselves at a crossroads,
independent automobile industry analysts say.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Complicating the situation is a drastic anti-inflation
program that has dried up consumers' money and forced
existing auto makers to slash production and send workers
home.
   Brazil's automobile industry, the world's 11th largest,
"will have to choose between producing better and cheaper
vehicles that can compete internationally or be squeezed out
of the market, most likely by Japanese automobile makers,"
said Amedeo Scabbia, of the Sao Paulo office of Technomic
Consultants International, a consulting firm based in
Evanston, Ill.
   The four automobile companies "have a kind of gentlemen's
agreement to not rock the boat," Mr. Scabbia said. "Since
there is no real competition among them, they don't have to
bother with developing more modern or fuel-efficient cars."
   Before taking office in March, President Fernando Collor
de Mello described Brazilian-made cars as "horse carts"
compared with those in other countries. On May 1, he ordered
a study on the feasibility of having other automobile
manufacturers operate in Latin America's largest country.
   "We have already been informally advised of the interest
of some industries, namely Japanese, to set up operations in
Brazil," said Marcos Caramuru, press spokesman for the
Economy Ministry.
   Mr. Caramaru said the entry of new automobile
manufacturers would break the cartel-like grip Volkswagen,
Ford, GM and Fiat have on the market.
   But industry leaders, such as Jacy Mendonca, president of
the National Automakers Association, say an invasion of
foreign auto makers is unlikely in the short run.
   "When we sold more than one million vehicles in 1979 no
one showed any interest in coming to Brazil," said Mr.
Mendonca, the local auto makers' main spokesman. "Why would
outsiders want to come now, when we expect to sell less than
700,000 units?"
   Mr. Mendonca said Japanese auto makers he consulted
"showed no interest in investing in Brazil. They are more
interested in the U.S., Asia, Mexico and Western and Eastern
Europe."
   Tadatsugu Tanaka, administrative director of the local
subsidiary of Toyota Motor Corp., said that "although we hope
to one day produce passenger cars in Brazil, that day won't
come for quite a while."
   Since starting operations in Brazil in 1958, Toyota has
produced only jeeps and light-duty trucks here.
   Mr. Tanaka said Brazil's local market was too small to
warrant massive investments needed to set up automobile
plants similar to others around the world.
   "For the moment, the investment priorities of Toyota,
Japan are in Europe, the U.S. and Asia," Mr. Tanaka said.
   To produce cheaper and more competitive cars the
government needs to lift a ban on imports of high-tech
components, and lower taxes, which currently represent more
than 40% of the final cost of a vehicle, Mr. Mendonca said.
   Brazil exports approximately 30% of its production, but to
enter First World markets, the Brazilian vehicle must include
several high-tech components that can only be imported if the
automobile is made for export.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0129
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0129.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Abreast of the Market:
   Industrials Resume Rally, Closing
   At New High of 2831.71 Points
   ----
   By Craig S. Smith
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C2
</SO>
<IN>
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
STOCK INDEXES (NDX)
</IN>
<LP>
   NEW YORK -- Stocks resumed their latest rally, sending the
Dow Jones Industrial Average to another all-time high.
   Pinnacle West climbed 28%, or 3 5/8, to 16 3/8 after
acknowledging that tireless PacifiCorp had presented it with
yet another acquisition proposal. Pinnacle has rejected three
previous PacifiCorp merger proposals in the past seven
months.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Eric T. Miller, chief investment officer at Donaldson,
Lufkin &amp; Jenrette, says the Pinnacle story is an illustration
that corporate buying is still the most important source of
demand for stock, whether it be through mergers, share
repurchases or the occasional leveraged buy-out.
   Pinnacle's news came against a backdrop of rising stock
prices as the market shrugged off a wider-than-expected trade
deficit for March, reported before the opening.
   Computer-driven buy programs spurred the industrial
average up 25 points before it settled back down to a gain of
12.03 points for the day, ending at 2831.71, a new closing
high for the index.
   Standard &amp; Poor's 500-Stock Index added 0.47 to 354.47,
while the New York Stock Exchange Composite Index rose 0.35
to 193.49.
   Big Board volume totaled 164,770,000 shares, up from
Wednesday's 159,810,000 shares. Advancers led decliners, 832
to 649.
   Donaldson Lufkin's Mr. Miller said the momentum may carry
over today. Others said, however, that May stock options and
future contracts expire today, leaving the market vulnerable
to unexpected swings.
   The next big psychological hurdle for equity investors
won't come until early June, when the Labor Department
releases data on the nation's May employment.
   The numbers are likely to clarify the economic picture
that was clouded by seasonal factors earlier in the year.
   Alcan Aluminium led the most active list, down 1/8 at 21
1/8 on volume of 5.3 million shares in apparent
dividend-related trading. The stock, which went ex-dividend
on Monday, led the most active list Wednesday on volume of
more than nine million shares.
   Traders said Texas Utilities was also high on the active
list because of trading tied to its dividend. The stock,
which carries an 8% dividend yield, goes ex-dividend May 29.
It rose 1/4 to 36 7/8 on volume of more than 2.2 million
shares. More than two million shares of the stock changed
hands Wednesday.
   Sotheby's Holdings was also high on the list with a 1/4
point gain to 18 7/8. The company held a huge auction of
impressionist and modern paintings last night.
   Safecard Services soared 1 to 8 3/4, a new 52-week high on
heavy volume after Wertheim Schroder recommended the stock.
   Philip Morris was active, easing 1/8 to 44 3/8. The
company's German subsidiary has agreed to acquire a cigarette
plant in East Germany, according to a report by the East
German news service ADN. Terms weren't disclosed.
   Trading in American Stores closed at 69, up 3 1/2 after a
delayed opening. The company has agreed to sell most of its
Alpha Beta stores, ending a 1 1/2 year antitrust battle with
the state of California over American Stores's $2.5 billion
acquisition of Lucky Stores. American Stores will continue to
operate Lucky but will sell 152 of Alpha Beta's 175 stores in
Southern California within the next five years.
   National Westminster Bank added 1 1/8 to 33 5/8. The U.K.
clearing bank is in "exclusive discussions" to buy Europeenne
de Banque from Credit Commercial de France, according to the
Financial Times. The acquisition, if completed, would more
than double NatWest's network in France, where its presence
has lagged behind Barclays and Midland.
   Federal National Mortgage Association added 5/8 to 38 3/4.
An important measure of the association's profitability
widened in April, suggesting that the company's profits got
off to a good start in the second quarter.
   SmithKline Beecham's American depositary receipts gained 1
1/2 to 41 3/4. Prudential-Bache Securities upgraded its
rating on the stock to a "buy" from a "hold," according to
Dow Jones Professional Investor Report.
   Shares of Digital Equipment Corp. slid 1, or 1.8%, to 87
3/8. Traders said the computer company's shares fell because
a trade magazine reported that shipments of Digital's new
VAX-9000 mainframe computer could be delayed a month or more.
A Digital Equipment spokesman acknowledged some delay in the
shipping schedule for the company's VAX-9000 but said it
would have "no revenue impact." Dallas Kirk, director of
public relations, said "the schedule has shifted somewhat,
but it's nothing significant." He also said orders for the
9000 "have been great."
   Hewlett-Packard continued to slide, losing 3/4 to 45 3/8
after dropping 1 7/8 Wednesday. The company's executives were
said to have taken a "cautious" tone in a conference call
with analysts after the release of fiscal second-quarter
results Wednesday, said the investor report. It said several
analysts lowered their 1990 earnings estimates over concern
about Hewlett's shift toward selling more lower-margin
products.
   New Jersey-based First Fidelity Bancorp. jumped 1 7/8 to
19 1/2. The company announced it will pay a reduced quarterly
dividend of 30 cents a share due to an expected loan-loss
provision in the second quarter of as much as $300 million.
The company said its internal loan portfolio review is near
completion.
   Shareholders of HomeFed had a different reaction to news
of a rise in nonperforming assets at HomeFed Bank. HomeFed
fell 2 to 30 after reporting that nonperforming assets rose
10% in April.
   Westpac Banking slid 1 5/8 to 18 5/8. The company reported
that its six-month operating profit fell 8% from a year
earlier.
   Tucson Electric Power fell 1/8 to 10 7/8. The company
raised the possibility that it might be forced to seek
bankruptcy-law protection from its creditors if various
financing plans aren't successful, The Wall Street Journal
reported.
   The American Stock Exchange Market Value Index rose 1.26
to 354.94. Volume totaled 13,760,000 shares compared with
12,190,000 Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
