<HL>
   Latest U.S. Demands for Market Access
   In Japan May Spur Strong Opposition
   ----
   By Christopher B. Wilcox
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A5C
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
BANKS (BNK)
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
</GV>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- The U.S. government intends to push for far
broader moves by Japan to open its financial markets, and the
tack could spur greater political opposition here than
previous discussions.
   In the past, the U.S. has primarily sought specific
openings for U.S. banks and securities firms into Japan's
financial markets on a case-by-case basis. But this time
around, the U.S. is seeking broad deregulation of deposit
rates, widespread direct dealings in the currency markets and
greater opportunity for foreign financial institutions to
manage Japanese cash.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Washington's wider approach may have the potential for big
payoffs to U.S. financial institutions, but there is also
greater risk of the U.S.-Japanese negotiations getting bogged
down in special-interest politics in Tokyo.
   The U.S. negotiating team will be headed by David Mulford,
the Treasury's undersecretary for international affairs,
while Japan's delegation will be headed by Makoto Utsumi, the
Finance Ministry's vice minister for international affairs.
The talks are scheduled for Monday and Tuesday; informal
discussions have been going on for some time.
   Washington's latest demands are viewed as threats by
Japan's smaller banks, its intimate network of money dealers
and its investment management industry. These institutions
have many allies in parliament, the Bank of Japan and the
Finance Ministry.
   "Japanese small- and medium-sized financial institutions
are strongly opposed to quick deregulation of interest
rates," says a bank regulator at the Finance Ministry, noting
that many feel they'll be unable to compete.
   He says the smaller Japanese banks "are very much afraid
that they will follow the path of U.S. savings and loan
institutions," many of which have collapsed in recent months.
   Then there is the question of how Japan's government-run
postal savings system would set rates if they were
aggressively deregulated, officials say.
   If the system chose to compete with the big banks by
jacking up rates, the move would hurt smaller financial
institutions, especially those outside the cities. If the
system set its rates lower, as the less competitive markets
outside the big cities allow, then it would lose market share
in urban centers to big banks.
   Furthermore, the prospect of higher yields in the postal
savings system isn't comforting to the government. If the
postal savings system has to pay higher yields, it
conceivably would have to collect more from its investments,
including the money it lends to the government.
   The potential cost to Japan's government of higher yields
in the postal savings system is just one example of the risk
of deregulating interest rates. Rising yields throughout the
financial system would threaten to push up the government's
cost of borrowing.
   Even though there is talk of a three-year timetable to
allow Japanese institutions to adapt to broad deregulation of
interest rates, that may not be long enough given the number
of Japanese institutions affected and the wariness of
regulators.
   In addition, the alarm of Japanese regulators about the
impact of futures and program trading on the stock market
makes them leery of aggressively pursuing another foreign
initiative. Stock-index futures were lobbied for by U.S. and
other foreign firms and governments, and foreign companies so
far have dominated use of the instrument.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0124
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0124.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   Trade Surplus
   Of Japan Fell
   51.4% in April
   ---
   Effect of Consumption Tax
   Cited; Exports Declined
   5.8% as Imports Rose 15%
   ----
   By Yumiko Ono
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<CO>
   JAPAN
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- A sharp rise in imports caused Japan's April
trade surplus to drop 51.4% from the year before, reversing a
widening of the surplus in March.
   The April trade surplus, measured on a customs-cleared
basis, fell to $3.54 billion from $7.29 billion a year
earlier, the Finance Ministry said. Exports fell 5.8% to
$21.87 billion from $23.22 billion, while imports rose 15% to
$18.33 billion from $15.93 billion. In March, the trade
surplus increased for the first time in nearly a year, rising
7.2% to $7.09 billion from $6.61 billion in March 1988.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Ministry officials said that both April's sharp decline
and March's increase in the surplus were in large part due to
distortions caused by the imposition of a 3% consumption tax
in April 1989. Imports were unusually low in April last year,
as consumers were discouraged to spend after the new tax made
prices higher. That heightened the increase in the
year-to-year comparison of imports. But a rush of last-minute
purchases in March 1989 had increased imports for that month,
and one result was the upturn in the surplus in March 1990.
   Nevertheless, the narrowing surplus came as a relief to
the Japanese government, which continues to receive U.S.
pressure to correct the bilateral trade imbalance. Both
countries are trying to improve their trade relationship by
removing structural impediments in their economies that
supposedly prevent Japan's surplus and the U.S. deficit from
shrinking.
   In April, the trade surplus with the U.S. declined a hefty
46.2%, to $2.45 billion from $4.54 billion a year earlier.
Exports to the U.S. fell 15.1% to $6.72 billion, while
imports rose 26.8% to $4.27 billion.
   The drop in the trade surplus last month convinced some
economists that the surplus will continue to narrow for a
while longer. Although Japan's surplus had been steadily
shrinking for most of the past year, many had feared that the
drop in the value of the yen against the dollar until
recently would encourage companies to step up exports again,
since dollar-denominated prices of Japanese goods would be
lower. The Ministry calculated April exports at 157.2 yen to
the dollar, compared with 132.12 yen a year earlier.
   The drop in the surplus "lets a little steam off the
argument that the weaker yen will lead to an export boom,"
said Paul Summerville, an economist for Jardine Fleming
Securities Ltd. Pressure from the Japanese government and
slower growth in the U.S. economy will also keep exports from
rising too quickly, Mr. Summerville said.
   But other economists noted that by a different measure,
Japan's trade surplus has been increasing gradually this
year. Seasonally adjusted figures for the first four months
of 1990 showed the surplus to be growing at an annualized
rate of $60 billion, said Hirohiko Okumura, chief economist
for Nomura Research Institute Ltd. In the final quarter of
1989, he said, the surplus grew at an annualized pace of $50
billion.
   In addition, said Mr. Okumura, "the surplus is expanding
despite a recent government import promotion program. That is
something to watch out for."
   Exports in April were especially weak to the U.S.
Shipments of autos to the U.S. fell 33.7% to $1.5 billion,
reflecting slow demand in the American market and increased
local production by Japanese auto makers, ministry officials
said. Exports of videocassette recorders to the U.S. also
dropped sharply.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0123
</DOCNO>
