<HL>
   Conferees Reach
   Pact on Big Parts
   Of Spending Bill
   ----
   By David Rogers
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12
</SO>
<CO>
   LATAM MDEST UTX AFRIC
</CO>
<IN>
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
ENVIRONMENT (ENV)
BANKS (BNK)
ECONOMIC NEWS (ECO)
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
CONGRESS (CNG)
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
INTERIOR DEPARTMENT (INR)
</GV>
<LP>
   WASHINGTON -- A House-Senate conference agreed on major
provisions of a spending bill that expedites aid to Panama
and Nicaragua and adds more than $3 billion to assorted
domestic accounts for the year ending Sept. 30.
   Negotiations continued on proposed reductions and
transfers within Pentagon accounts to accommodate the new
expenditures, but the appropriations leadership appeared
confident that a package will be enacted before the Memorial
Day recess beginning next week.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Amendments on abortion rights and the death penalty were
stripped from the measure last night, and House Democrats
agreed to insert waivers intended to expedite the Central
American aid if lawmakers can't agree on related authorizing
legislation.
   The action represents a concession to President Bush, but
the victory carries a high price tag. The domestic portion of
the bill has grown steadily under the pressure of lawmakers,
and influential members seized the opportunity to initiate
home-state projects and allow the transfer of funds to pay
for House members' election-year mail.
   Environmentalists blunted an effort by Southern
agriculture interests to weaken federal wetlands protections.
But in a little-noticed fight over the future of the private
U.S. space industry, the conference approved language seeking
to block the participation of a United Technologies Corp.
subsidiary in an Australian launch facility.
   The Central American aid -- $420 million for Panama and
$300 million for Nicaragua -- represents the bulk of Mr.
Bush's initial request this spring. But the administration
still faces a difficult floor fight next week on the related
question of imposing conditions on U.S. military assistance
to El Salvador.
   Democrats have picked up significant support for their
demand that 50% of the assistance be withheld through fiscal
1991, and Rep. John Murtha (D., Pa.,), chairman of the
Defense Appropriations Subcommittee, joined in backing an
amendment to give the civilian Cristiani government greater
control of the funds.
   Mr. Murtha's leadership is significant because of his ties
to fellow moderates and Southern conservatives, and a strong
vote would add to the pressure on the State Department to
withhold a substantial portion of any new Salvadoran military
aid in fiscal 1991. "They have to go to 50% in `91," said Mr.
Murtha. "We're funding the military, and the military has to
reform."
   The Central America debate brought two former House
speakers, James Wright and Thomas O'Neill, back into the fray
in an unusual display of letters to their former colleagues.
Mr. Wright, who resigned a year ago, has appealed to members
to first expedite passage of the aid to Nicaragua and Panama,
while Mr. O'Neill's letter directly addresses the El Salvador
question and supports the conditions on future aid.
   Apart from the Central American assistance, the bill
includes a total of $55 million distributed among accounts
for the Caribbean, Chile and Africa. An estimated $75 million
in supplemental funds are provided for U.S. refugee programs,
and in a related provision, Israel would get $400 million in
loan guarantees for housing of incoming Soviet Jews. Under
pressure from the House, fees to the U.S. for the guarantees
were increased to $2.8 million up front, but a $125,000
ceiling is set on annual fees charged to the Jerusalem
government.
   Defense negotiators last night appeared determined to
block construction of a costly Louisiana explosives plant
previously protected by the Senate, but among domestic
accounts, the pattern was one of accommodation.
   Senate Appropriations Committee Chairman Robert Byrd
emerged with a $185 million down payment on a new Federal
Bureau of Investigation fingerprint facility for his home
state of West Virginia, and the laundry list of smaller
additions ran from a Great Lakes research vessel to a earthen
dam in northern California.
   House lawmakers, who are spending far beyond their
appropriated allotment for mail this year, won broad
authority to transfer as much as $25 million in unobligated
funds from other accounts to meet the projected deficit.
   And while adding an estimated $177 million to firefighting
accounts in the Bureau of Land Management, the conference
also provided that $77 million be used to replenish other
Interior Department accounts that were tapped in meeting the
costs of fires last year.
   Among business interests, the bill would force the
administration to proceed with the so-called
interest-equalization program of the Export-Import Bank,
effectively providing $20 million for what would be a $200
million loan program to encourage exports.
   By contrast, the provision related to United Technologies
grows out of an effort by Senate Commerce Committee Chairman
Ernest Hollings to curb export licenses for American
technology or satellites in private efforts using Soviet or
Chinese-built launchers.
   Though allowing for a presidential waiver in cases
involving national security, the South Carolina Democrat
first attached satellite restrictions last fall to an
appropriations bill funding the Commerce Department. The
added language now is intended to apply the same restrictions
to those providing technical services, and committee staffers
said the provision was opposed by United Technologies because
of the impact on a subsidiary's application to participate in
a Cape York, Australia, space facility that might use the
cheaper Soviet or Chinese launchers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0047
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0047.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Bid Sweetened
   By PacifiCorp
   For Pinnacle
   ---
   Takeover Offer Is Increased
   To $1.82 Billion, or $21
   A Share, and Is All Cash
   ----
   By Rhonda L. Rundle
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A3
</SO>
<CO>
   PPW PNW
</CO>
<IN>
TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)
ELECTRIC UTILITIES (ELC)
</IN>
<LP>
   PacifiCorp resumed its pursuit of Pinnacle West Capital
Corp. with a substantially sweetened $1.82 billion takeover
bid that's all cash and that drops conditions that made it
easier for Pinnacle to reject three previous offers.
   PacifiCorp said its $21-a-share offer includes assumption
of Pinnacle debt of about $1.1 billion and, by removing the
earlier conditions, is intended to be as "clean and clear to
understand" as possible.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   If the bid is accepted, the combined company would sell
power in eight states and would realign power production and
transmission in the lucrative western U.S. markets.
   A.M. Gleason, PacifiCorp president and chief executive
officer, said in a letter made public after being sent to
Richard Snell, Pinnacle's chairman, that "it is time to bring
to a conclusion PacifiCorp's expressions of interest."
   Mr. Snell said in an interview that Pinnacle's financial
advisers are studying the proposal, which will be "seriously
considered by the board." Pinnacle might have a response "in
a few days," he said. The next regular board meeting is set
for Wednesday after the annual meeting, but Mr. Snell said a
board meeting might be held before then.
   The proposal follows a meeting Tuesday between Messrs.
Gleason and Snell in Portland, Ore., where PacifiCorp is
based. While no formal offer was presented, Mr. Gleason "gave
me a range," Mr. Snell said. In response to a reporter's
question, he said that "in times past (Mr. Gleason) has said
he wouldn't do a hostile situation; there was some intimation
that he might," now.
   In New York Stock Exchange composite trading yesterday,
Pinnacle shares jumped $3.50 to $16.25 on volume of 2.2
million shares. PacifiCorp shares fell 75 cents to $22.25
with 362,000 shares changing hands.
   Phoenix, Ariz.-based Pinnacle's principal asset is Arizona
Public Service Co., the state's largest utility. The company
also owns two small investment units and recently sold its
unprofitable uranium-mining operations. PacifiCorp is an
electric utility whose service territories cover parts of
seven states.
   Pinnacle had rejected PacifiCorp's earlier offers as
inadequate and not in the best interests of shareholders; but
the tone of Mr. Snell's remarks yesterday seemed somewhat
more receptive, analysts said. They suggested that the cash
terms and amount of the latest offer make it very attractive
and thus difficult for Pinnacle's board to reject.
   In February, PacifiCorp offered to swap 0.88 new
PacifiCorp common share for each of Pinnacle's 86.8 million
shares. PacifiCorp valued the bid at $1.69 billion, or $19.47
a share, but Pinnacle said a number of conditions sharply
reduced the offer's value. One analyst said he valued the bid
as low as $10 a share.
   PacifiCorp first emerged as a bidder for Pinnacle's
Arizona Public Service unit in November, when Pinnacle stock
was trading at $5.25 a share. The company was considering a
bankruptcy-law filing because of the financial drain from its
MeraBank thrift unit. In March, Pinnacle was released by
regulators of all financial obligations to the thrift after
making a $465 million infusion of capital into it.
   "I don't see how (Pinnacle) can refuse" the latest offer,
said Daniel Rudakas, an analyst with Duff &amp; Phelps Inc. in
Chicago. "Maybe it's possible to build a case" for $21 a
share, "but I'm amazed." Some of the conditions that were
dropped effectively guaranteed the value of certain Pinnacle
assets, he said.
   Other analysts were less worried that PacifiCorp might be
paying too much. "It's a very fair value for Pinnacle even
assuming that the company might accomplish some financial
recovery on its own over the next few years," said Barry
Abramson at Prudential-Bache Securities Inc.
   Last year, Pinnacle had a net loss of $551.4 million,
including a $676 million loss from discontinued operations,
on revenue of $1.51 billion.
   From the perspective of PacifiCorp holders, Mr. Abramson
said that the proposed acquisition might be "a bit dilutive"
but strategically sound in the long run. PacifiCorp's
territory isn't growing much and despite Arizona's
real-estate problems it has one of the fastest-growing
populations in the country, the analyst said. Last year,
PacifiCorp posted net income of $465.6 million, or $3.62 a
share, on revenue of $3.72 billion.
   PacifiCorp has said that the proposed acquisition would
give it new routes to transmit power to rich California
markets. In addition, PacifiCorp's Northwest markets need
peak power during winter months, while the Southwest needs
peak power during summer months, allowing more efficient use
of peak-power generation.
   PacifiCorp's reputation as one of the nation's most
aggressive thrifts is underscored by its dogged pursuit of
Pinnacle. PacifiCorp said it has discussed its bid with its
banks and other lenders and they have indicated that "this is
a feasible transaction."
   Any bank borrowings made in connection with the offer
would be paid down with proceeds from equity offerings, the
company said. Pinnacle's financial advisers are First Boston
Corp. and Salomon Brothers Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0046
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0046.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International Brief -- Royal Dutch/Shell Group:
   Net Income for 1st Quarter
   Fell 36% to $1.37 Billion
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<CO>
   RD SC
</CO>
<IN>
EARNINGS (ERN)
OIL, INTEGRATED MAJORS (OIL)
PETROLEUM (PET)
</IN>
<LP>
   Royal Dutch/Shell Group said first-quarter net income
dropped 36% to #816 million ($1.37 billion) from #1.28
billion a year earlier, within analysts' expectations on a
historic-cost basis, accounting for changes in values of
inventories.
   On a current-cost basis, valuing the company's oil
inventories at current market prices, profit fell 26% to #826
million from #1.11 billion. Operating profit edged up 2.8% to
#1.48 billion from #1.44 billion.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Earnings per share for Royal Dutch Petroleum Co., the
Dutch arm, fell 45% to 3.03 guilders ($1.64), and for Shell
Transport &amp; Trading Co., the British segment, dropped 36% to
9.1 pence a share.
   Sales rose 22% to #17.5 billion from #14.3 billion a year
earlier. Excluding taxes and excise duties, sales rose 24% to
#14.2 billion from #11.4 billion.
   Shell's exploration and production operations surged 73%
to #508 million. Refining and marketing lines fell 15% to
#290 million, hurt by a #14 million loss in the U.S. from
higher raw material costs. In the 1989 first quarter, Shell
had a #57 million gain in the U.S. Chemical profit plummeted
56% to #159 million; U.S. chemical sales fell. Coal and
metals earnings were flat.
</TEXT>
