<HL>
   What's News --
   World-Wide
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A1
</SO>
<LP>
   GORBACHEV MET with Lithuania's premier to discuss
Vilnius's secession bid.
   In what was considered a major breakthrough in a
two-month-old confrontation over the Baltic republic's
proclamation of independence, the Soviet leader held two
hours of talks in the Kremlin with Lithuania's Prime Minister
Prunskiene, who traveled to Moscow with an offer of new
concessions. The official Tass news agency reported that
Gorbachev reaffirmed that the republic must rescind its
declaration, saying Lithuania's proposal to suspend its
secession drive and remain part of the Soviet security system
didn't address the issue.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State Baker, reportedly deadlocked in
arms-control talks in Moscow with Shevardnadze, said he would
meet today with Prunskiene to discuss the situation in the
breakaway state.
   ---
   Bush and West Germany's Kohl held talks in Washington on
German unification and other East-West issues. The president,
preparing for this month's superpower summit, expressed
support for a united Germany with "full control over all its
territory," and said reunification should end the allies'
postwar rights in Germany.
   ---
   The Pentagon announced that the U.S. isn't asking NATO
allies to increase defense budgets by 3% a year, a reversal
of longstanding policy. The decision, which was to be
unveiled at a meeting of defense ministers next week, came
amid an extensive review by the alliance of its military
needs amid the political changes in East Europe.
   ---
   Bush said that while he won't tolerate discrimination in
hiring, he would reject any legislation that imposes quotas
on employers. Following the president's White House comments,
congressional Democrats and Republicans unveiled a compromise
amendment to an anti-bias measure that is intended to deal
with Bush's objections.
   ---
   About 150,000 state employees returned to work in
Nicaragua, ending a weeklong strike that crippled services in
Managua and strained the nation's already troubled economy.
As part of the settlement, President Chamorro's government
agreed to double the salaries of the public workers.
   ---
   The Dominican Republic's Bosch accused conservative
President Balaguer of fraud in Wednesday's presidential
election, and he called for street demonstrations. Partial
returns from the nationwide balloting showed the leftist
former president, who was toppled in a 1963 coup, trailing
Balaguer.
   ---
   A jury in Brooklyn convicted a white teen-ager of
second-degree murder in the racial slaying of 16-year-old
black Yusuf Hawkins in August 1989. Joseph Fama, 19, accused
of being the triggerman in the killing in the New York City
borough, faces 25 years to life in prison. A second jury is
deliberating the case against a co-defendant.
   ---
   Romanian politicians concluded campaigning for Sunday's
presidential and parliamentary balloting, the country's first
free elections in 53 years. While about 70,000 backers of
interim President Iliescu rallied in Bucharest, tens of
thousands of demonstrators branded him a "neo-Communist."
   ---
   The republic of Slovenia appeared headed for a clash with
Yugoslavia's federal authorities, saying it would resist any
emergency measures to restrict its autonomy. Belgrade's
eight-member presidency announced Wednesday that it would
take "urgent steps" to prevent separatist moves.
   ---
   A special London investigator said some members of the
British army have passed intelligence documents to loyalist
Protestant terrorists in Northern Ireland. The data
reportedly was about Irish Republic Army members. The
official said 94 people had been arrested as a result of the
inquiry.
   ---
   Police in South Korea fought stone-throwing students in
Kwangju and a dozen other cities, part of nationwide protests
called by a dissident coalition to mark today's 10th
anniversary of a crushed anti-government rebellion in the
southern city. In Ulsan, 27,000 workers at the nation's
largest car plant continued a strike for a third day.
   ---
   Negotiators in Manila attempted to break a deadlock over
the future of U.S. military bases in the Philippines, failing
to resolve a dispute over whether Washington has made full
payments for the installations. The round of talks is
scheduled to end today.
   ---
   Israel's President Herzog granted Prime Minister Shamir a
21-day extension on his mandate to form a new government.
Shamir had cited disputes with potential partners over the
distribution of cabinet posts. The country's Labor-Likud
coalition collapsed March 15 over Shamir's refusal to accept
U.S. proposals for Israeli-Palestinian talks.
   ---
   South African police guarded a gold mine in Welkom, about
180 miles south of Johannesburg, after two whites were killed
Wednesday in a clash with black workers. In Brussels,
President de Klerk, who is on a nine-nation tour, said he
wouldn't let extremists of any type interfere with his plans
to ease South Africa's apartheid system.
</TEXT>
