<HL>
   Soviets Fail to Pay on Steel
   From Japan; Orders Held
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C9
</SO>
<CO>
   FREST J.NIP J.SMM J.NKK J.KWS
</CO>
<IN>
STEEL MANUFACTURERS (STL)
MONETARY NEWS, FOREIGN EXCHANGE, TRADE (MON)
INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC NEWS AND STATISTICS (IEN)
</IN>
<LP>
   TOKYO -- Four Japanese steel companies have halted
production of steel pipes ordered by the Soviet Union, a
further sign of the foreign-exchange difficulties shackling
the Soviet economy.
   Nippon Steel Corp., Sumitomo Metal Industries Ltd., NKK
Corp. and Kawasaki Steel Corp. temporarily stopped the output
at the beginning of May, because they hadn't received any
payment since the beginning of the year. They are holding
orders for delivery between April and September of 130,000
tons of pipes for drilling and shipping oil.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Though the companies will probably continue to do business
with Soviet organizations, they won't resume production until
payment is guaranteed, a Nippon Steel spokesman said. This is
the first time that the Soviet Union has delayed payments
this long, he said. The companies have sent a group of
trading company officials to the U.S.S.R. to request a
guarantee for the shipments.
   Japan recently doubled the rate on export insurance for
steel shipments to the Soviet Union. Japanese trading houses
also have been notifying the government they hadn't received
payment for textiles and chemical products. Moscow owes as
much as an estimated $200 million to Japanese companies. The
Soviet Union also has been delaying payment on orders to
other countries, even for necessities such as grain.
   After the decentralization of the Soviet economy last
year, autonomous trading organizations sprouted nationwide,
and some have been unable to secure enough currency to pay
their bills. But major Soviet procurement agencies were
faulted in the steel pipes case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0019
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0019.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Ex-Northrop Aide
   Sentenced to Prison
   In Falsifying Tests
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A2
</SO>
<CO>
   NOC
</CO>
<IN>
AEROSPACE (ARO)
</IN>
<GV>
DEFENSE DEPARTMENT (DEF)
JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)
</GV>
<LP>
   LOS ANGELES -- The former manager of Northrop Corp.'s
now-defunct Precision Products division was sentenced in
federal court here to three years in prison and fined $10,000
for his role in falsifying tests on the Air Force's
air-launched cruise missile.
   Clarence Gonsalves, 62 years old, pleaded guilty in
February to one count of conspiracy and seven counts of
making false statements. Most of the counts related to his
ordering an underling to make it appear that certain tests on
the missile were successful when they weren't.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Los Angeles Assistant U.S. Attorney William Fahey said Mr.
Gonsalves's guilty plea helped force Northrop to reach a plea
agreement with the government in February. Just as opening
arguments in the criminal fraud trial against the aerospace
company were to begin, Northrop pleaded guilty to 34 counts
of making false statements to the government in connection
with the testing of parts for the cruise missile and the
Navy's Harrier jet. The company also agreed to pay $17
million in fines.
   As part of that settlement, the Justice Department agreed
to drop 141 additional counts. It also dismissed all charges
against the two highest-ranking corporate officials
implicated in the case, divisional executives Joseph Yamron
and Leopold Engler, who were reinstated by Northrop after the
settlement. As part of the agreement, federal authorities
also closed their investigations into alleged improprieties
related to Northrop's making of MX missile parts and the B-2
bomber.
   ---
   Corrections &amp; Amplifications
                                                                                                       

   CLARENCE GONSALVES is a former manager of the now-defunct
Western Services Department, Pomona, Calif., of Northrop
Corp.'s Precision Products division, and Howard Hyde is a
former senior engineer of the department. Recent editions
mistakenly said that the Precision Products division,
Norwood, Mass., was the unit that closed.
   (WSJ May 23, 1990)
</TEXT>
