<HL>
   U.S. Glassmaker Finds French Politics
   Can Make Foreign Investment Fragile
   ----
   By E.S. Browning
   Staff Reporter of The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   F.STG EUROP
</CO>
<LP>
   PARIS -- In a burst of deregulation, France in 1988
abolished most government controls on foreign investment.
Non-French companies supposedly now can build new plants here
without even notifying the government.
   Actual practice, however, is different. Politics still is
deeply entwined with business, as U.S. glassmaker Guardian
Industries Corp. is discovering.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   Guardian plans to build a new flat-glass plant in southern
Europe, probably in northern Spain or near Nimes in southern
France. The plant would cost 700 million French francs ($126
million) and create about 250 jobs initially. Later expansion
could add another 500 jobs, sources here say.
   With unemployment in the Nimes region running as high as
15%, the French government was preparing to offer Guardian a
hefty subsidy for choosing Nimes. The European Community
allows subsidies as high as 17% of the project cost in
depressed regions such as this one, and French sources say
discussions have "advanced very well."
   But there is a hitch: Guardian's big French competitor,
Cie. de Saint-Gobain, is furiously lobbying to block the
subsidy. Saint-Gobain just got through building its own new
flat-glass plant a few hundred miles away, near Grenoble, and
its own subsidy was less than 10% of cost. (The exact level
is a subject of some dispute.) Since the Grenoble region is
more prosperous, EC rules didn't permit Saint-Gobain a bigger
subsidy.
   The complex Guardian case illustrates how politics often
is thrust into European investment decisions, even when laws
seem designed to prevent it.
   With the EC planning to bring down internal trade barriers
by the end of 1992, foreign companies are racing to set up
European subsidiaries, and European countries are competing
actively for the business. Although supposedly regulated by
the EC, subsidies are endemic.
   This case is particularly sensitive. By coincidence,
French Industry Minister Roger Fauroux is a former
Saint-Gobain chairman. On top of that, Saint-Gobain is in the
process of completing the friendly takeover of U.S. abrasives
maker Norton Co. of Massachusetts. But however sensitive the
case may be, Saint-Gobain isn't holding back.
   Its position is simple: Saint-Gobain says it can't believe
its own government is helping a major competitor get started
in its own back yard.
   "We don't want Guardian to get a higher subsidy than we
got," says a Saint-Gobain official. The official recognizes
that Saint-Gobain could have received a larger subsidy if it
had located in a less-prosperous region, but he says that
isn't the point.
   "France already has five flat-glass plants, three of which
belong to us," he says. "If another gets built, we could face
excess production. We aren't saying they can't come. We're
just saying we don't want the government to create this
problem itself, through excess generosity."
   But while the government in the past blocked foreign
investment in order to protect local manufacturers, that
isn't supposed to happen any more. "We would rather have
foreign plants than unemployment," Mr. Fauroux is fond of
saying.
   Reality is somewhat different. The subsidy's total value
is up to the government, as long as it stays within the EC
limits. So the French government now is split between
Saint-Gobain backers, arguing for a low subsidy, and
development experts and local officials, who want a big
subsidy to ensure that the factory doesn't go to Spain.
   French officials insist that Saint-Gobain's lobbying won't
influence their decision, and that they will offer Guardian
an excellent incentive. "We are very favorable to the arrival
of this company," says one official.
   Officials at closely held Guardian, reached at their
headquarters in Michigan, declined to comment. Sources here
say a decision is expected within a month.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0009
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0009.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   International:
   France's Bull Denies
   Press Report of Spying
   Against U.S. Firms
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A7
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP IBM TXN
</CO>
<IN>
COMPUTERS AND INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (CPR)
</IN>
<LP>
   PARIS -- French computer maker Cie. des Machines Bull
denied a French press report alleging that France's
intelligence service carried out industrial espionage against
International Business Machines Corp., Texas Instruments Inc.
and other U.S. technology companies.
   The report, in the news magazine L'Express, said the
French foreign espionage service, the Direction Generale de
la Securite Exterieure, recruited senior officials at the
U.S. companies' French subsidiaries. The article claimed that
senior French government officials were worried that, without
the espionage, Bull would have trouble catching up with the
competition.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   It said the theft of research and marketing secrets began
around 1987 and ended late in 1989 when the U.S. Federal
Bureau of Investigation and Central Intelligence Agency
confronted the spies. The executives in question were fired,
the magazine said, and the news covered up to avoid scandal.
   Spokesmen for IBM in Armonk, N.Y., and for Texas
Instruments in Dallas declined to comment, as did the French
government. The head of security at Texas Instruments' Nice
headquarters said he wasn't aware of any espionage. He said
that there is a regular turnover in management officials at
Texas Instruments' French subsidiary but that he isn't aware
of anyone being fired for stealing secrets.
   A Bull official said the company posted a loss of 267
million francs ($48.1 million) last year, compared with
profit of 303 million francs in 1988. But the official said
Bull is on the mend, is advancing through an aggressive
acquisition strategy and operates entirely independently of
the French government.
   "We formally deny this report," said the Bull official.
"We haven't any relationship with the DGSE."
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0008
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0008.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   Brussels Exchange
   Tangles With Media
   Over Flow of Facts
   ---
   News Groups Criticize Plan
   By Bourse to Distribute
   Information on Market
   ----
   By Peter R. Greiff
   Special to The Wall Street Journal
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION
</SO>
<CO>
   EUROP RTRSY
</CO>
<IN>
SECURITIES INDUSTRY (SCR)
STOCK MARKET, OFFERINGS (STK)
MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)
</IN>
<LP>
   BRUSSELS -- The usually unaggressive Brussels stock
exchange and a handful of Belgian and international news
groups have clashed in recent weeks over just whose job it is
to get the facts out.
   News groups, including Reuters Ltd., say the little Bourse
de Bruxelles is seeking to act as a monopoly, violating
European Community competition rules and principles of press
freedom. Reuters is a unit of London-based Reuters Holdings
PLC.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   The Brussels exchange, meanwhile, says it is protecting
the integrity of the Belgian market, ensuring a fair and
orderly playing field for all participants.
   In the latest development in the controversy, the Belgian
Finance Ministry said yesterday that the government is
reviewing the proposals in response to complaints by the
media. The government plans to issue a report in two weeks.
   The squabble in Belgium, not traditionally a leader in EC
financial markets, could be a trial run for a much bigger
battle as 12 Community stock exchanges move to form an
EC-wide trading system.
   At stake is who controls the information investors see and
when they see it.
   If the Belgian bourse has its way, it will become a
clearinghouse for news about companies, receiving
market-affecting corporate announcements before the news
groups, and then distributing them to market participants
through a bourse-operated information system.
   News groups, like other market watchers, would have access
to the announcements by subscribing to a bourse computer data
service, for what exchange officials say will be a reasonable
fee.
   The news groups are crying foul. In an 18-page letter sent
last week to the Belgian government, Reuters and several
Belgian news organizations complained that giving the bourse
such a role would go against the spirit and letter of EC laws
on transparency and competition.
   Moreover, many don't trust the Brussels bourse to get the
company information to the public quickly and without risk of
insider trading.
   "This could institutionalize insider trading," said Herman
Smedts, manager of electronic information at the electronic
publishing arm of Flemish language financial daily De
Financieel Ekonomische de Tijd.
   Even if the bourse could process the information smoothly
and quickly, the disclosure first to subscribers of the stock
market data service would discriminate against foreigners or
institutions who aren't regular market participants, Mr.
Smedts and others said.
   Bourse officials, however, say their way would prevent
insider trading by giving the bourse a chance to suspend
trading in a share before the information is released.
   Also, they say, by timing the release of news to
after-bourse hours, the bourse could assure small investors
will see reports in newspapers the next day, and be able to
act with the same information as market professionals.
   "We are mainly concerned that information gets to all
people at the same time," said Jean Peterbroek, chairman of
the Commission of the Bourse and of a leading Brussels
brokerage firm,, Peterbroek van Campenhout et Cie.
   Money, for the news groups and the bourse, is also at
stake. The bourse, a nonprofit corporation, recently set up a
company called SA Bourse-Data-Beurs NV (BDB) to sell data.
The news groups say by channeling information to its fully
owned subsidiary, the bourse is giving BDB a monopoly.
   The real purpose of BDB, they say, is to pay for the
computer trading system the Brussels bourse bought in 1988.
   Bourse officials don't deny they intend to offset their
costs through BDB, but say they are not out to gouge
subscribers either.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>
WSJ900518-0007
</DOCNO>
<DOCID>
900518-0007.
</DOCID>
<HL>
   New Securities Issues
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C19
</SO>
<CO>
   FORGN EUROP
</CO>
<IN>
BOND MARKET NEWS (BON)
MORTGAGES, MORTGAGE BANKERS, MORTGAGE-BACKED SECURITIES (MOR)
</IN>
<GV>
TREASURY DEPARTMENT (TRE)
VETERANS AFFAIRS DEPARTMENT (VET)
</GV>
<LP>
   The following were among yesterday's offerings and
pricings in U.S. and non-U.S. capital markets, with terms and
syndicate manager, as compiled by Dow Jones Capital Markets
Report:
                                                                                                       

                       CORPORATES
                                                                                                       

</LP>
<TEXT>
   Dow Capital -- $150 million of debentures, due May 15,
2010, priced as 9% securities at 99.87 to yield 9.032%. The
noncallable debentures, which may be put back to the company
on May 15, 1995, were priced at a spread of .42 percentage
point above the Treasury's when-issued five-year note. Rated
single-A-1 by Moody's Investors Service Inc. and single-A by
Standard &amp; Poor's Corp., the issue will be sold through
underwriters led by Goldman Sachs &amp; Co.
   Asian Development Bank -- $300 million issue of notes, due
June 1, 2000, priced as 9 1/8% securities at 99.195 to yield
9.25%. The noncallable notes were priced at a spread of .56
percentage point above the Treasury's 10-year note. The
issue, rated triple-A by both Moody's and S&amp;P, will be sold
through underwriters led by Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
                                                                                                       

                          MUNICIPALS
                                                                                                       

   Nassau County, N.Y. -- $85.1 million of various purpose
revenue bonds, due July 1, 1991-2009, apparently were won by
a Prudential-Bache Capital Funding group with a bid setting
the net interest cost at 6.99%. The bonds, insured and rated
triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P, were priced for reoffering to
yield from 6.00% in 1991 to 7.10% in 2008 and 2009. The issue
consists of $71.5 million of general improvement bonds and
$13.6 million of sewer district bonds. There are no term
bonds.
                                                                                                       

                      MORTGAGE-BACKED
                                                                                                       

   Goldman, Sachs &amp; Co. -- two separate $300 million issues
of real estate mortgage investment conduit securities backed
by Government National Mortgage Association 9 1/2%
securities. The offerings are being made through GS Trust 8A
and GS Trust 8B. Details on yields weren't immediately
available.
   Veterans Administration -- $348.7 million of mortgage
securities backed by its Vendee mortgages through an
underwriting group headed by First Boston Corp. The offering
is being made through American Housing Trust VI. Vendee loans
are made by the VA to buyers of homes taken over by the VA
after defaults on VA-guaranteed mortgages. This issue is
backed by the VA, whose guarantee is supported by the U.S.
government. For classes with details available, the
securities yield as much as 10.113%, or 1.45 percentage point
over the 30-year Treasury, for a security with an average
life of 20.5 years. The collateral consists of Vendee loans
with a weighted average coupon rate of 9.53% and weighted
average remaining term to maturity of 29 years. The issue is
rated triple-A by Moody's and S&amp;P.
                                                                                                       

                       EUROBONDS
                                                                                                       

   Finnish Export Credit (Finland) -- #200 million ($338.6
million) of 16% bonds due Dec. 2, 1991, priced at 101 7/8,
via Merrill Lynch International.
   KFW International Finance Inc. (West Germany) -- $300
million issue of 9 1/4% bonds due June 12, 1995, at a fixed
reoffer price of 99 5/8 to yield 9.35% reoffered, via
Deutsche Bank Capital Markets. Guaranteed by Kreditanstalt
fuer Wiederaufbau.
   World Bank (agency) -- 125 million European currency units
of 10 3/8% bonds due June 27, 1995, priced at 101.55, to
yield 10.43% less fees, via Credit Commercial de France. Fees
1 3/4.
   Nationwide Anglia Building Society (United Kingdom) --
#100 million of floating-rate notes due June 1995, priced at
100 and paying interest at 0.10 point above the three-month
London interbank offered rate, via Baring Brothers.
   Council of Europe (agency) -- 150 million Swiss francs
($106.8 million) of 7 1/4% public bonds due June 18, 2000,
priced at 101, via Banca del Gottardo. Callable from June 18,
1998, at 101.
</TEXT>
