<HL>
   GM Says It Will Idle
   Facility in Georgia
</HL>
<DATE>
05/18/90
</DATE>
<SO>
WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A4
</SO>
<CO>
   GM F C HMC TOYOY NSANY J.MZD SBRU J.IZM J.MOT
</CO>
<IN>
AUTOMOBILES (AUT)
</IN>
<LP>
   DETROIT -- General Motors Corp. said it will indefinitely
idle its Lakewood, Ga., assembly plant beginning Aug. 6
because of slow sales of the 1990-model Chevrolet Caprice
full-sized car and the Buick Estate Wagon station wagon.
About 2,200 workers will be affected.
   The No. 1 auto maker had announced its plans to idle the
Lakewood plant in September, but didn't specify then when the
closing would take place.
</LP>
<TEXT>
   GM said it has scheduled daily and weekend overtime at its
Janesville, Wis.; Lordstown, Ohio; Orion, Mich., and Lansing,
Mich., assembly facilities.
   Ford Motor Co. has planned overtime at its Wixom, Mich.;
Kansas City and St. Louis, Mo.; Twin Cities, Minn., and
Louisville, Ky., assembly plants.
   Overall, the 10 major U.S. car makers planned to build
138,967 this week, down 11.2% from 156,524 a year ago.
